 white, Writing Immigration presents a unique interplay of leading scholars and journalists working on the contentious topic of immigration. In a series of powerful essays, the contributors reflect on how they struggle to write about one of the defining issues of our time—one that is at once local and global, familiar and uncanny, concrete and abstract. Highlighting and framing central questions surrounding immigration, their essays explore topics including illegal immigration, state and federal mechanisms for immigration regulation, enduring myths and fallacies regarding immigration, immigration and the economy, immigration and education, the adaptations of the second generation, and more. Together, these writings give a clear sense of the ways in which scholars and journalists enter, shape, and sometimes transform this essential yet unfinished national conversation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEmigration and immigrationxPress coverage. 0aEmigration and immigration. 0aPolitical science. 0aSocial sciences. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aamerican anthropology.  aamerican dream.  aamerican immigration.  acoming to america.  acultural anthropology.  acultural studies.  aemigration and immigration.  afederal immigration regulation.  aillegal immigration.  aimmigration and education.  aimmigration and journalism.  aimmigration and the economy.  aimmigration misconceptions.  aimmigration myths.  aimmigration reform.  aimmigration scholars.  aimmigration studies.  arefugees and asylees.  arefugees and migrants.  asocial scientists.  astate immigration regulation.  athe second generation.1 aBernstein, Nina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChiswick, Barry R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voca